Bash Alias Dotfiles Setup — Notes
Goal

The goal of this assignment was to create a custom bash environment and store the configuration files inside a dotfiles repository.

Dotfiles are configuration files (files that start with .) that customize how the Linux shell behaves.

Using a repository allows the configuration to be:

reused on other machines

version controlled

easily installed with a script

Step 1 — Create Bash Aliases

Aliases are shortcuts for commands in the terminal.

Example:

alias ll="ls -alF"

This means when I type:

ll

it runs:

ls -alF

which shows a detailed directory listing.

I created a file called:

~/.bash_aliases

and added useful command shortcuts.

Example aliases used:

alias ll="ls -alF"
alias la="ls -A"
alias l="ls -CF"
alias ..="cd .."
alias update="sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y"

These make the terminal faster and easier to use.

Step 2 — Load the Aliases

After creating the file, I loaded it into my shell with:

source ~/.bash_aliases

The source command reloads the file so the terminal recognizes the new aliases.

I tested the aliases by running:
ll

If the directory listing appeared, the alias was working.

Step 3 — Create the Dotfiles Repository Folder

To store my configuration files, I created a repository folder:
mkdir ~/dotfiles

Inside that repository I created a folder called:
homefiles

Final structure:

~/dotfiles
   └── homefiles
Step 4 — Copy Bash Configuration into the Repository

I copied my alias file into the repository so it can be version controlled.

Command used:
cp ~/.bash_aliases ~/dotfiles/homefiles/

Now the repository contains my shell customization file.

Step 5 — Create an Install Script

I created a script called:
install.sh

This script automatically installs the configuration when run.

The script does three main things:
Backs up existing alias files
Creates a symbolic link
Ensures bash loads the alias file

Example command used in the script:
ln -s ~/dotfiles/homefiles/.bash_aliases ~/.bash_aliases
A symbolic link is like a shortcut that points to the file in the repository.

This means if the file changes in the repository, the system automatically uses the updated version.

Step 6 — Reload the Shell Environment

After installing the aliases, the shell must reload the configuration.

Command used:
source ~/.bashrc

This applies the new configuration to the current terminal session.

Step 7 — Documentation

I created a README.md file that explains:
what the files do
how to install them
where the alias ideas came from
how AI was used to help generate examples

